Notebook 3 - Effects of Using Fewer Layers¶

Overview¶

This notebook is the modification of notebook 2 changing the source to test and experiment on fewer convolutional layers to study its effect on the output.

The findings in this notebook will be taken into account when working on any future notebooks.

Here's the citation for the original paper where the VGG16 network is described in detail:

Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition, K. Simonyan, A. Zisserman, arXiv:1409.1556

# Dependecies
from __future__ import print_function
import os
import time
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
from keras import backend as tf
from keras.models import Model
from keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16
from scipy.optimize import fmin_l_bfgs_b
from scipy.misc import imsave

# Define the content loss function
def content_loss(content, combination):
    return tf.sum(tf.square(combination - content))

# Define the total variation loss, without this the image will come out noisy.
def total_variation_loss(x):
    a = tf.square(x[:, :height-1, :width-1, :] - x[:, 1:, :width-1, :])
    b = tf.square(x[:, :height-1, :width-1, :] - x[:, :height-1, 1:, :])
    return tf.sum(tf.pow(a + b, 1.25))

# Define the gram matrix
def gram_matrix(x):
    features = tf.batch_flatten(tf.permute_dimensions(x, (2, 0, 1)))
    gram = tf.dot(features, tf.transpose(features))
    return gram

# Defne the style loss functions
def style_loss(style, combination):
    S = gram_matrix(style)
    C = gram_matrix(combination)
    channels = 3
    size = height * width
    return tf.sum(tf.square(S - C)) / (4. * (channels ** 2) * (size ** 2))

# Define a method that calculates the loss and gradient
def eval_loss_and_grads(x):
    x = x.reshape((1, height, width, 3))
    outs = f_outputs([x])
    loss_value = outs[0]
    grad_values = outs[1].flatten().astype('float64')
    return loss_value, grad_values

# Convert to greyscale, but keep RGB so that it works with VGG16
def greyscale(image):
    img = Image.new("RGB", image.size, (255, 255, 255))
    xmax, ymax = image.size
    for y in range(ymax):
        for x in range(xmax):
            r, g, b = image.getpixel((x, y))
            p = int(0.2126*r + 0.7152*g + 0.0722*b)
            tuple = p, p, p
            img.putpixel((x, y), tuple)
    return img

# Object for L-BFGS method 
class Evaluator(object):

    def __init__(self):
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grads_values = None

    def loss(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is None
        loss_value, grad_values = eval_loss_and_grads(x)
        self.loss_value = loss_value
        self.grad_values = grad_values
        return self.loss_value

    def grads(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is not None
        grad_values = np.copy(self.grad_values)
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grad_values = None
        return grad_values

#Set the desired size of the image
height = 512
width = 512

# base image directory path
image_path = 'images/'

# Load content reference image
content_image_filename = 'Sasha.png'
content_image_path = image_path + content_image_filename
tmp_content_image = Image.open(content_image_path)
tmp_content_image.load() # required for .split()

# Check if PNG of JPG, remove alpha if PNG.
content_ext = os.path.splitext(content_image_path)[1]
if(content_ext == '.png'):
    # Convert RBGA format to a simple RGB format
    tmp_content_image_split = tmp_content_image.split()
    if(len(tmp_content_image_split) == 4):
        content_image = Image.new("RGB", tmp_content_image.size, (255, 255, 255))
        content_image.paste(tmp_content_image, mask=tmp_content_image_split[3])
    else:
        content_image = tmp_content_image
elif(content_ext == '.jpg'):
    content_image = tmp_content_image
else:
    raise ValueError('Content image file must either be a JPG or a PNG file')

# Resize the Image
content_image = content_image.resize((height, width))

# Convert to greyscale
content_image = greyscale(content_image)
content_image

# Load the style reference image.
style_image_filename = 'Torean_bw.png'
style_image_path = image_path + style_image_filename
tmp_style_image = Image.open(style_image_path)
tmp_style_image.load() # required for .split()

# Check if PNG of JPG, remove alpha if PNG.
style_ext = os.path.splitext(style_image_path)[1]
if(style_ext == '.png'):
    # Convert RBGA format to a simple RGB format
    tmp_style_image_split = tmp_style_image.split()
    if(len(tmp_style_image_split) == 4):
        style_image = Image.new("RGB", tmp_style_image.size, (255, 255, 255))
        style_image.paste(tmp_style_image, mask=tmp_style_image_split[3])
    else:
        style_image = tmp_style_image
elif(style_ext == '.jpg'):
    style_image = tmp_style_image

style_image

# Add an extra dimensions so that it can be used with VGG16
content_array = np.asarray(content_image, dtype='float32')
content_array = np.expand_dims(content_array, axis=0)
content_array.shape

style_array = np.asarray(style_image, dtype='float32')
style_array = np.expand_dims(style_array, axis=0)
style_array.shape

# Not sure, tweaking vals?
content_array[:, :, :, 0] -= 103.939
content_array[:, :, :, 1] -= 116.779
content_array[:, :, :, 2] -= 123.68
content_array = content_array[:, :, :, ::-1]

style_array[:, :, :, 0] -= 103.939
style_array[:, :, :, 1] -= 116.779
style_array[:, :, :, 2] -= 123.68
style_array = style_array[:, :, :, ::-1]

# Tensorflow variables
content_image = tf.variable(content_array)
style_image = tf.variable(style_array)
combination_image = tf.placeholder((1, height, width, 3))

# Create the input tensor for VGG16
input_tensor = tf.concatenate([content_image,
                                    style_image,
                                    combination_image], axis=0)

# Create the VGG16 model
model = VGG16(input_tensor=input_tensor, weights='imagenet',
              include_top=False)

# Create a dictionary for the layers from VGG16
layers = dict([(layer.name, layer.output) for layer in model.layers])

# Set how much content will be retained and how much style to transfer
content_weight = 0.025
style_weight = 5.0
total_variation_weight = 1.0

# Create the loss variable
loss = tf.variable(0.)

# Retrieve from our dictionary the layer for our content
layer_features = layers['block2_conv2']

content_image_features = layer_features[0, :, :, :]
combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]

# Define the loss function using tensors
loss += content_weight * content_loss(content_image_features,
                                      combination_features)

# Define the style loss funciton using tensors, must iterate because we need to do it for all layers.
for layer_name in feature_layers:
    layer_features = layers[layer_name]
    style_features = layer_features[1, :, :, :]
    combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]
    sl = style_loss(style_features, combination_features)
    loss += (style_weight / len(feature_layers)) * sl
    
# Define it using tensors
loss += total_variation_weight * total_variation_loss(combination_image)

# Define the gradients
grads = tf.gradients(loss, combination_image)

# Define the outputs as the loss
outputs = [loss]
outputs += grads
f_outputs = tf.function([combination_image], outputs)

evaluator = Evaluator()

# Perform gradient decsent using L-BFGS
x = np.random.uniform(0, 255, (1, height, width, 3)) - 128.

iterations = 10

for i in range(iterations):
    print('Start of iteration', i)
    start_time = time.time()
    x, min_val, info = fmin_l_bfgs_b(evaluator.loss, x.flatten(),
                                     fprime=evaluator.grads, maxfun=20)
    print('Current loss value:', min_val)
    end_time = time.time()
    print('Iteration %d completed in %ds' % (i, end_time - start_time))
    
# Remove the extra bias dimension, re-adjust the RGB values and clip them.
x = x.reshape((height, width, 3))
x = x[:, :, ::-1]
x[:, :, 0] += 103.939
x[:, :, 1] += 116.779
x[:, :, 2] += 123.68
x = np.clip(x, 0, 255).astype('uint8')

# Output the image for viewing.
stylized_image = Image.fromarray(x)
stylized_image

August 15th, 2017 - Table Observations¶

It took awhile to get all 32 images done but it has been managed. Below you'll see a table of the compiled resutls.

The row and column labels are binary numbers representing which layers are used to produce the output image.

(000, 00) (row, column) means that none of the feature layers were used, in this case I just put the original image of myself.

A more useful example: Take (010, 11), convert to a single binary number my concatenating the values like so, '010' + '11' (rrr + cc). This gives us a single binary number: 01011. With this number we can tell which layers were used. Each binary digit represents wheather a layer has been used. The left most digit tells us if layer 5 was included in the feature layers while the right most is for layer 1.

More examples:

(000, 01) -> 00001 -> Only layer 1 was used. (101, 10) -> 10110 -> Layers 5, 3, 2, were used.

Furthur¶

The complied image table below can be use to deduce certain characteristics each layer provides to the output image; such as, what's describe in the following table.

Layer # Observations
1 When not included, network has hard time reproducing
the greyscale style from the base style image;
must extract local contrast and colour.
2 When not included, network has hard time reproducing
the stylistic lines from the base style image;
must extract local edges.
3 When included, the image's contrast bandwith seems to
get smaller; it becomes less variant in tone.
4 When included, some of the finer noise lines vanish. Line taper.
5 Line smoothness goes down when not included; smaller less wanted lines show up.
Lines are more connected when included.

Having ways to extract similarities from the image to determine precisely, visually, what's similar would be useful. The above table is not all inclusive as there is so much my human eyes can distinguish between the 32 images. Even subtracting image values and normalizing would be useful.

August 18th, 2017 - Notebook Review¶

Each layer seems to provide some part of the style to the image. Layer 1 is doing local contrast & colour, providing the greyscale image. Layer 2 is doing fine lines. Layer 3 removes some of the lines, but also reduces the overall variation in the greyscale (reduces bandwidth). The higher we get the smoother and more continuous the lines are.

If I wanted to created a end to end pretrained network that produced images using the Torean_bw.png style then I'd have to generate a huge image data set to train it. I would have to look at every output image and either accept it or not. This would require more time then I have for this project; however, it would be a fun project.
